<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="967" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[861,1505,202,756]" pageId="23" pageNumber="967">
<emphasis box="[906,978,452,475]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="967">Note. –</emphasis>
There are several syntypes mentioned (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="967">G.C. Pringle &amp; C. Conzatti</emphasis>
under no. 
<emphasis box="[1124,1255,482,506]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="967">Conzatti 231</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[1269,1458,482,506]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="967">G.C. Pringle 6713</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[861,1047,513,538]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="967">G.C. Pringle 5787</emphasis>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Greenman, J. M." box="[1067,1247,514,538]" journalOrPublisher="Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts" pageId="23" pageNumber="967" pagination="47 1 - 4 89" part="33" refId="ref25608" refString="Greenman, J. M. 1898. Diagnoses of new and critical Mexican Phanerogams. Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts 33: 47 1 - 4 89." title="Diagnoses of new and critical Mexican Phanerogams" type="journal article" year="1898">Greenman (1898)</bibRefCitation>
commented on differing foliar characters in the latter number, so we selected the most widely distributed gathering as the lectotype from the first two numbers. Most of the specimens have a branch from a pistillate and a staminate individual mounted together on the same sheet, so we assume that they are from the same gathering.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[861,1505,202,756]" pageId="23" pageNumber="967">Taxonomic status: Probably a natural entity (monophylum) as currently defined (A).</paragraph>
